      <field name="fulltext">THE TWO GEORGES: A Dialogue of the Dead. By R. H. HORNE. Guelph. Where's my wig!âwig!âthe little close-crimp'd styleâ Powder and pig-tailâcock'd-hat with low crown; Brown coat and waistcoat, brown smalls, stockings brownâ Shoe-buckles, knee-bucklesâGeorge, you smileâyou smile, Like morning o'er the great Atlantic wave! Still, somewhat grave. Alive, you never smiled, 'tis said: You can afford one now you're dead. Washington. I had no time for smiles. Guelph. That's very true! Very trueâvery trueâit is exceedingly true! The British gave you something else to do. Yesâand you did it. Ah, you're not much changed: Neither am I, though somewhat disarranged. But I should look as trim and plain, New risen from my tombâ Too sturdily self-will'd for disdain,â As though, from Windsor come, Direct to London town.â Though now a Shadeâwho once wore England's crown. I do rejoice to see your âstars,â Which then so grieved me in our wars! Washington. King-Shade! 'tis better men should forget some things, And leave the mind a clear field for new deeds; The more so when the memory chafes or bleeds, Which may confuse or clog our onward wings. Guelph. I think so, now:âthere is no doubt Death makes us wiser, and we see Behind, around, and onward through the rout Of people, soldiers, politicians, And fools with âmissions,â And state perplexities,â Besides one's ownâone's ownâthink, think of thatâ A bull-head will that burst through this cock'd hat! Washington. And you may bear in mind, regretfully, Though now we have easy heartsâcontented powerâ Remonstrances most filial met a shower Of stone-cold words, or bullets for reply. Guelph. Yesâyesâyou had some hard words, George, And after that, a bayonet-charge. Some bullets tooâbrown-bess ones;âso had we! You very nearly drove us into the seaâ Yesâinto the Atlantic sea! At any rate, quite close upon the shore: And soldiers with no drums and fifes of glee, Soon had to sail homeâtroubling you no more. Washington. But you saw none the clearer, old King George, Nor were your ministers the best of men: You were convinced against your will, for thenâ And some while afterâyou would fain re-forge The anchor whose hot flukes we cast off from our shores. Guelph. Shade of the Brave!âre-open not old sores! Taxes, you know, seem natural to Kings. We gave your freedomâbut we wanted moneyâ (Like my son âWales,â Who was much troubled by a man named âBoney,!â) My memory fails,â And in my brain an unknown conflict sings! Oh, I am stubbornâproud as hoary; But evermore I thought of England's glory, Centred within my crown!â That you will own, Man of few wordsâ (More guns and swords) Lay then upon my tomb forgiving flowers! Washington. My country does so!âand your poets sing Of English-speaking people's future powers. Guelph. George Washington! shake hands with your old King, Who did you so much wrongâyou, his best son! The bull-head crown that you cast-off, Hath long since ceas'd to fret for more dominions Than PhÅbus shines upon; And Conquest's pinions Are folded like an iron ring, Ne'er to unclasp: our old flag's staff No more to plant except on friendly shores. But yours?âa different Destiny, (Needing no keen prophetic eye) Revealsâas far as Southern Ocean roars.</field>
